Inheritance in Java
âœ… Definition (Interview Line)

Inheritance is a mechanism where one class acquires the properties and behavior of another class using the extends keyword.

class Animal {

    void eat() {
        System.out.println("Animal is eating");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {

    void bark() {
        System.out.println("Dog is barking");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Dog d = new Dog();

        d.eat();   // inherited method
        d.bark();  // own method
    }
}
ğŸ–¥ Output
Animal is eating
Dog is barking
ğŸ”¥ What Happened Here?
Dog extends Animal

So Dog gets eat() automatically

No need to rewrite code

ğŸ‘‰ This improves code reusability

ğŸ”¹ Types of Inheritance in Java
Type	Supported?
Single	âœ… Yes
Multilevel	âœ… Yes
Hierarchical	âœ… Yes
Multiple (class to class)	âŒ No
Multiple (using interface)	âœ… Yes
ğŸ”¥ Example of Multilevel
class Animal {
    void eat() {
        System.out.println("Eating");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    void bark() {
        System.out.println("Barking");
    }
}

class Puppy extends Dog {
    void weep() {
        System.out.println("Weeping");
    }
}
Puppy now has:

eat()

bark()

weep()

ğŸ¯ Interview Short Answer
Inheritance allows a child class to reuse the properties and methods of a parent class. 
It is achieved using the extends keyword and promotes code reusability.

How Inheritance is Achieved in Java?

ğŸ‘‰ Using the extends keyword (for classes)
ğŸ‘‰ Using the implements keyword (for interfaces)




